\section{Introduction \& Problem Statement}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\textbf{ChaatCheck} is an end-to-end deep learning system for classifying Indian street food images. Given a photograph of food, the system:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Predicts the \textbf{dish name} from 12 possible street food classes
  \item Returns a \textbf{confidence score} for the prediction
  \item Displays \textbf{calorie estimates} per serving
  \item Shows \textbf{colour-coded allergen badges} (Gluten, Dairy, Nuts)
  \item Lists \textbf{key ingredients}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Motivation}

India's street food ecosystem is enormous and culturally diverse. Identifying dishes by photograph is non-trivial due to variations in preparation, plating, lighting, and regional style. Building an automated classifier has practical applications in dietary tracking, menu digitisation, and allergen safety.

\subsection{Scope — Task T2.4 (Street Food Tier 1)}

This project implements Tier 1 of Task T2 from the SMAI assignment specification, targeting 12 street food classes drawn from the master 80-class Indian Food Images dataset. The 12 classes were selected for their distinct visual signatures and prevalence in North and South Indian street food culture.

\begin{infobox}[Dataset Source]
\href{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/iamsouravbanerjee/indian-food-images-dataset}{Indian Food Images Dataset} — Kaggle (iamsouravbanerjee). 4,000+ images across 80 food categories. Licensed for educational use.
\end{infobox}

