\section{Data Preparation Pipeline}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The data preparation phase was executed in two sequential Jupyter notebooks on Google Colab (GPU: NVIDIA T4).

\subsection{Phase 1A — Acquisition \& Splitting (\texttt{Phase\_1\_Data\_Prep.ipynb})}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Mount Google Drive} — all outputs persist across Colab sessions via \texttt{/content/drive/MyDrive/SMAI\_Assignment3/}.
  \item \textbf{Configure Kaggle API} — credentials set via environment variables and \texttt{\textasciitilde/.kaggle/kaggle.json}.
  \item \textbf{Download dataset} — the full 355 MB archive is pulled directly using \texttt{kaggle datasets download}.
  \item \textbf{Extract archive} — unzipped to \texttt{full\_dataset\_80\_classes/}. The internal structure is \texttt{Indian Food Images/Indian Food Images/<class>/}.
  \item \textbf{Filter to 12 classes} — only the 12 street food folders are copied; the remaining 68 classes are ignored.
  \item \textbf{Split per class} — each class folder is shuffled and split at indices \texttt{int(N*0.70)} and \texttt{int(N*0.85)}.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Core split logic from Phase\_1\_Data\_Prep.ipynb}]
for cls in street_food:
    imgs = [f for f in os.listdir(src) if f.lower().endswith(('.png','.jpg','.jpeg'))]
    random.shuffle(imgs)
    train_idx, val_idx = int(len(imgs)*0.7), int(len(imgs)*0.85)

    for name, split in [
        ('train', imgs[:train_idx]),
        ('val',   imgs[train_idx:val_idx]),
        ('test',  imgs[val_idx:])
    ]:
        dst = os.path.join(output_dir, name, cls)
        os.makedirs(dst, exist_ok=True)
        for img in split:
            shutil.copy(os.path.join(src, img), os.path.join(dst, img))
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Phase 1B — Offline Augmentation (\texttt{Phase\_1\_Perform\_Augmentation.ipynb})}

With only 35 images per class in training, the model is highly prone to overfitting. To mitigate this, offline augmentation was applied: each original image generates \textbf{2 additional augmented versions}, tripling the effective training set size.

\subsubsection{Augmentation Pipeline}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Augmentation transforms applied per image}]
aug_pipeline = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
    transforms.RandomRotation(degrees=15),
    transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2, contrast=0.2)
])
\end{lstlisting}

Augmented images are saved alongside originals with the naming convention \texttt{<basename>\_aug1.jpg}, \texttt{<basename>\_aug2.jpg}. Only training images are augmented; validation and test sets remain untouched to simulate real-world inference conditions.

