\section{Model Architecture}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Base Model — MobileNetV2}

MobileNetV2 was chosen as the base architecture for its excellent accuracy-to-parameter ratio, making it well-suited for deployment in a lightweight Streamlit app. It uses depthwise separable convolutions and inverted residuals with linear bottlenecks.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{MobileNetV2 Architecture Summary}
\label{tab:arch}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabular}{@{} ll @{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
Architecture         & MobileNetV2 \\
Pretrained weights   & ImageNet (1,000 classes) \\
Input size           & $224 \times 224 \times 3$ \\
Last channel width   & 1,280 \\
Modified layer       & \texttt{classifier[1]} \\
Output classes       & 12 (street food) \\
Total parameters     & $\approx 3.4\text{M}$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Transfer Learning Strategy}

The final fully-connected classifier layer was replaced with a new linear layer mapping from 1,280 features to 12 output logits:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Classifier head replacement}]
model = models.mobilenet_v2(pretrained=True)
model.classifier[1] = nn.Linear(model.last_channel, 12)
\end{lstlisting}

All convolutional layers retained their ImageNet pre-trained weights. Fine-tuning was applied to the full network (not frozen) to allow domain adaptation to food images.

\subsection{Inference Transform}

At inference time, images are pre-processed with a deterministic pipeline (no augmentation):

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Inference pre-processing pipeline (model\_inference.py)}]
transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((224, 224)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    # Note: ImageNet normalisation can be added here for improved accuracy
])
\end{lstlisting}

Softmax is applied over the 12 logits to obtain class probabilities, and \texttt{torch.max} selects the predicted class and its confidence score.

