\section{Limitations \& Future Work}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Current Limitations}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Small dataset:} Only 50 original images per class. The model has not seen enough real-world diversity in lighting, angle, and plating styles.
  \item \textbf{Validation oscillation:} Accuracy fluctuates across epochs, indicating the model is sensitive to the small validation set (only 7 images per class).
  \item \textbf{No ImageNet normalisation:} The inference transform omits mean/std normalisation, which may reduce accuracy compared to a properly normalised pipeline.
  \item \textbf{Static metadata:} Calorie estimates are hard-coded approximations, not queried from a structured nutrition database.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Proposed Improvements}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Expand dataset:} Scrape additional images from food blogs or use the IFCT 2017 dataset for more nutrition accuracy.
  \item \textbf{Add ImageNet normalisation:} Apply mean \texttt{[0.485, 0.456, 0.406]} and std \texttt{[0.229, 0.224, 0.225]} to potentially improve accuracy by 3--5\%.
  \item \textbf{Learning rate scheduler:} Use \texttt{CosineAnnealingLR} or \texttt{ReduceLROnPlateau} to avoid the observed oscillation in validation accuracy.
  \item \textbf{Confusion matrix analysis:} Add per-class accuracy reporting to identify which classes the model struggles with most.
  \item \textbf{Expand to Tier 2 / Tier 3:} Scale from 12 to 30 or all 80 classes using progressive training.
  \item \textbf{Mobile deployment:} Export to ONNX or TorchScript for real-time on-device inference.
\end{enumerate}

