\section{Conclusion}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

ChaatCheck demonstrates that transfer learning with MobileNetV2 is effective even on a small, domain-specific dataset of Indian street food images. Starting from just 600 raw images (50 per class), the system achieves a best validation accuracy of \textbf{83.33\%} after offline augmentation and 10 epochs of fine-tuning. The end-to-end pipeline — from Kaggle data acquisition through augmentation, training, and a fully functional Streamlit deployment — is modular, reproducible, and documented for extension to broader food recognition tasks.

The allergen detection and calorie estimation features make this a practically useful tool beyond a pure academic exercise, with real-world relevance for dietary tracking and food-safety applications.

